<subSubSection id="C358655E86056B23FEC58979FDB5F949" pageId="23" pageNumber="86" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BFD36D586056B23FEC58979FDB5F949" blockId="23.[236,1220,1015,1746]" pageId="23" pageNumber="86">
Remarks. This is an extremely rare species. 
<taxonomicName id="4C424D5686056B23FBCE8979FB58FAAF" authorityName="Knight" authorityYear="1930" box="[1046,1218,1293,1332]" class="Gastropoda" family="Pseudozygopleuridae" genus="Cyclozyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coenogastropoda incertae sedis" pageId="23" pageNumber="86" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B936EAC786056B23FBCE8979FB58FAAF" box="[1046,1218,1293,1332]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="86">Cyclozyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. (PI. 19 figs 5-8) from 'Kyndalyn' resembles C. 
<taxonomicName id="4C424D5686056B23FF35891DFE66FA0B" authority="Yoo" authorityName="Yoo" box="[237,508,1385,1424]" class="Gastropoda" family="Pseudozygopleuridae" genus="Cyclozyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coenogastropoda incertae sedis" pageId="23" pageNumber="86" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="sinusigera">
<emphasis id="B936EAC786056B23FF35891DFE04FA0B" box="[237,414,1385,1424]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="86">sinusigera</emphasis>
Yoo
</taxonomicName>
in shell shape and ornamentation, but differs in having closely spaced collabral lirae on teleoconch. Only two specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C424D5686056B23FC5E89B2FBAEFA77" authorityName="Knight" authorityYear="1930" box="[902,1076,1478,1516]" class="Gastropoda" family="Pseudozygopleuridae" genus="Cyclozyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coenogastropoda incertae sedis" pageId="23" pageNumber="86" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B936EAC786056B23FC5E89B2FBAEFA77" box="[902,1076,1478,1516]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="86">Cyclozyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. are obtained. The systematic position of 
<taxonomicName id="4C424D5686056B23FC608987FBFFF981" authorityName="Knight" authorityYear="1930" box="[952,1125,1523,1562]" class="Gastropoda" family="Pseudozygopleuridae" genus="Cyclozyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coenogastropoda incertae sedis" pageId="23" pageNumber="86" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B936EAC786056B23FC608987FBFFF981" box="[952,1125,1523,1562]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="86">Cyclozyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was discussed by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD34B2486056B23FE348A55FD61F9D3" author="Knight, J. B." box="[492,763,1569,1608]" pageId="23" pageNumber="86" refId="ref25807" refString="Knight, J. B., 1930 a. The gastropods of the St. Louis, Missouri, Pennsylvanian outlier: the Pseudozygopleurinae. Journal of Paleontology 4, Supplement 1, 88 pp." type="book" year="1930">Knight (1930a)</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD34B2486056B23FCAB8A55FEFBF9ED" author="Hoare, R. D. &amp; M. T. Sturgeon" pageId="23" pageNumber="86" pagination="850 - 858" refId="ref25615" refString="Hoare, R. D. &amp; M. T. Sturgeon, 1978. The Pennsylvanian gastropod genera Cyclozyga and Hemminthozyga and the classification of the Pseudozygopleuridae. Journal of Paleontology 52 (4): 850 - 858." type="journal article" year="1978">Hoare &amp; Sturgeon (1978)</bibRefCitation>
. The North American species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C424D5686056B23FC6E8A3BFBF9F9ED" authorityName="Knight" authorityYear="1930" box="[950,1123,1615,1654]" class="Gastropoda" family="Pseudozygopleuridae" genus="Cyclozyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coenogastropoda incertae sedis" pageId="23" pageNumber="86" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B936EAC786056B23FC6E8A3BFBF9F9ED" box="[950,1123,1615,1654]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="86">Cyclozyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have more strongly developed revolving costellae and are more attenuate in form.
</paragraph>
